ngdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hansen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Lars, Nels, Niels, Thor, Jorgen, Knud, Holger, Morten, Nils, Einer, Johan.","Danish, Norwegian, Dutch, Flemish, and North German: patronymic from the personal name   Hans  . This is the most common surname in Norway. Compare   Hanson   4 and also 2 below.","Americanized form of Norwegian, North German, Dutch, Flemish, and Danish   Hanssen  , a variant of 1 above. Compare   Hansson   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Hanse","meanings":["Dutch: variant of   Hansen  .","German: variant of   Hans  .","German: habitational name from a place called Hansen in Lower Saxony."]},{"name":"Hans","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ananta, Bhim, Chander, Gopal, Madhur, Malkit, Nirmal, Preet, Puneet, Ravi, Rohit, Roop.  German Erwin, Guenther, Helmut, Gerhard, Hermann, Klaus, Kurt, Manfred, Merwin.","German and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Hans</i>, a shortened form of <i>Johannes</i> (see   John  ). This surname is also found in France (Vosges, Alsace, Lorraine, and Nord). It is also borne by Ashkenazic Jews, presumably as an adoption of the German or Dutch surname.","Indian (Punjab): Arora and Sikh name, from Sanskrit <i>hamsa</i> ‘swan’ or ‘goose’."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes Hansen was born in 1467, in Rothbury, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom, her father, John Hansen, was 25 and her mother, Cicely Ravenshaw, was 21. She married John Rowland II in 1482, in Northumberland, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died on 9 November 1559, in her hometown, at the age of 92."},"et":{"1467–9 November 1559":"1467–9. november 1559","1467–1559":"1467–1559","1452–1520":"1452–1520","1482–1582":"1482–1582","1442–1520":"1442–1520","1447–1468":"1447–1468","1447":"1447","1468":"1468","1467":"1467","1520":"1520","1442":"1442","9 November 1559":"9. november 1559","1452":"1452","1582":"1582","1482":"1482","about 1482":"umbes 1482","1559":"1559","Rothbury, Northumberland, England":"Rothbury, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England","Rothbury, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Rothbury, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1467–9 November 1559":"1467–9. marraskuuta 1559","1467–1559":"1467–1559","1452–1520":"1452–1520","1482–1582":"1482–1582","1442–1520":"1442–1520","1447–1468":"1447–1468","1447":"1447","1468":"1468","1467":"1467","1520":"1520","1442":"1442","9 November 1559":"9. marraskuuta 1559","1452":"1452","1582":"1582","1482":"1482","about 1482":"noin 1482","1559":"1559","Rothbury, Northumberland, England":"Rothbury, Northumberland, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England","Rothbury, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Rothbury, Northumberland, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1467–9 November 1559":"1467–9 novemb